\maketitle

\begin{definition}
  A category $\cC$ is \emph{additive} if: it is enriched in $\Ab$; it
  has a zero object; for every $A,B\in \cC$ there is a product
  $A\times B$.
\end{definition}
For additive categories, finite products are the same as finite
coproducts.

Recall that the kernel of $f:B\to C$ is a map $i:A\to B$ with $fi=0$
and which is universal w.r.t. this property. Dually for cokernels.

\begin{definition}
  A category $\cC$ is \emph{abelian} if: it is additive; all kernels and
  cokernels exist; all monomorphisms are kernels and all epimorphisms
  are cokernels.
\end{definition}


